 currently performed in the contexts of war, insurgency and activism. Photographs, videos, interactive simulations and other kinds of images steer drones to their targets, train soldiers, terrorise the public, celebrate protest icons, uncover injustices, or call for help. They are often parts of complex agential networks and move across different media and cultural environments. This book is a pioneering interdisciplinary study of the role and function of images in political life. Balancing theoretical reflections with in-depth case studies, it brings together renowned scholars and activists from different fields to offer a multifaceted critical perspective on a crucial aspect of contemporary visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMass media and war. 0aMass media and world politics. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aImage operations.  aInsurgency.  aMilitary.  aPolitical conflict.  aTerrorism.  aVisual Culture.  aVisual media.  aWarfare.1 aAzoulay, Ariella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevrim Gürsel, Zeynep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEder, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEder, Jens, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElkins, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhosh, Bishnupriya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankey, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https: